definition.value: A chromocenter adjacent to the nucleolus.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with double-stranded methylated DNA. Methylation of cytosine or adenine in DNA is an important mechanism for establishing stable heritable epigenetic marks.
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methionine + 3-polyprenyl-4,5-dihydroxybenzoate -eq- S-adenosyl-L-homocysteine + 3-polyprenyl-4-hydroxy-5-methoxybenzoate + H+.

label.value: DNA methylation on cytosine within a CG sequence

definition.value: The covalent transfer of a methyl group to C-5 or N-4 of a cytosine located within a CG sequence in a DNA molecule.

label.value: DNA methylation on cytosine within a CNG sequence

definition.value: The covalent transfer of a methyl group, to C-5 or N-4, of a cytosine located within a CNG sequence in a DNA molecule. N stands for any nucleotide.

label.value: DNA methylation on cytosine within a CHH sequence

definition.value: The covalent transfer of a methyl group, to C-5 or N-4, of a cytosine located within an asymmetric CHH sequence in a DNA molecule. H stands for an adenine, cytosine, or thymine nucleotide.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with abscisic acid, plant hormones that regulate aspects of plant growth.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a methylated cytosine|unspecified|guanine trinucleotide.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with a methylated cytosine|unspecified|unspecified trinucleotide.

Catalysis of the reaction -  ATP + 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoic acid + coenzyme A -eq- AMP + diphosphate + 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoyl-CoA + H+. 3-oxo-2-(2'-pentenyl)-cyclopentane-1-octanoic acid is also known as OPC-8 - 0.
Catalysis of the oxidative cleavage of carotenoids.
Catalysis of the oxidative cleavage of carotenoids at the (9, 10) and|or (9', 10') double bond.

A small round nuclear body, measuring 0.2-0.8 microns in diameter that is diffusely distributed throughout the nucleoplasm. Several proteins known to be involved in miRNA processing have been localized to these structures. D-bodies are thought to be involved in primary-miRNA processing and|or storage|assembly of miRNA processing complexes.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of an ion by a channel that opens in response to a light stimulus.
Combining with nerve growth factor (NGF), to prevent apoptosis in neurons and promote nerve growth, or to initiate a change in cell activity.

The process in which a gene's sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + alpha-D-mannose 1-phosphate -eq- GDP-alpha-D-mannose + alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + alpha-D-glucose 1-phosphate -eq- alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate + GDP-alpha-D-glucose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP-L-galactose + myo-inositol 1-phosphate -eq- alpha-L-galactose-1-phosphate + GDP-myoinositol.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP + D-glucose 1-phosphate -eq- phosphate + GDP-glucose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  GDP + L-galactose 1-phosphate -eq- phosphate + GDP-galactose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + histone H3 -eq- CoA + acetyl-histone H3.
Catalysis of the reaction -  acetyl-CoA + histone H4 -eq- CoA + acetyl-histone H4.
Catalysis of the transfer of a solute or solutes from one side of a membrane to the other according to the reaction -  Mn2+(in) + H+(out) -eq- Mn2+(out) + H+(in).
Catalysis of the reaction -  S-adenosyl-L-methioninamine + spermidine -eq- S-methyl-5'-thioadenosine + thermospermine + H+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-galactose + N-glycan -eq- galactose-beta-1,3-N-glycan + UDP.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-4-keto-6-deoxyglucose -eq- UDP-4-keto-rhamnose.
Catalysis of the reaction -  UDP-4-keto-rhamnose + NADPH -eq- UDP-rhamnose + NADP+.
Catalysis of the reaction -  alpha-L-arabinose 1-phosphate + UTP -eq- UDP-L-arabinose + diphosphate.
A dense aggregation in the cytosol composed of proteins and RNAs that appear when the cell is under stress.
A posttranscriptional gene silencing process in which the silencing signal originates in a tissue separate from the tissue in which the silencing takes place.

Stops, prevents or reduces the activity of a telomerase. Telomerase catalyzes the reaction -  deoxynucleoside triphosphate + DNA(n) -eq- diphosphate + DNA(n+1). Catalyzes extension of the 3'- end of a DNA strand by one deoxynucleotide at a time using an internal RNA template that encodes the telomeric repeat sequence.
Catalysis of the transfer of nitrate from the inside of the cell to the outside of the cell across a membrane.
Modulates the activity of a metalloenzyme. A metalloenzyme is any enzyme that contains metal.
Increases the activity of a metalloenzyme. A metalloenzyme is any enzyme that contains metal.

Complex that possesses NAD(P)H dehydrogenase (plastoquinone) activity. The complex is one of the components of the electron transport chain. It is involved in electron transport from an unidentified electron donor, possibly NADH, NADPH or ferredoxin(Fd) to the plastoquinone pool.

label.value: production of lsiRNA involved in RNA interference

definition.value: Cleavage of double-stranded RNA to form lsiRNA (long small interfering RNA), a class of siRNAs 30 to 40 nt in length. lsiRNAs are induced by pathogen infection or under specific growth conditions.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression after the production of an RNA transcript.

label.value: mRNA localization resulting in posttranscriptional regulation of gene expression

definition.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression after the production of a mRNA transcript by its transport into, or maintainance in, a specific location within the cell.

label.value: regulation of mRNA stability involved in response to stress

definition.value: Any process that modulates the propensity of mRNA molecules to degradation that is part of a change in state or activity of a cell as a result of an exogenous disturbance.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription by transcription factor catabolism

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA-dependent transcription using a mechanism that involves the catabolism of a sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor by hydrolysis of its peptide bonds, initiated by the covalent attachment of ubiquitin, and mediated by the proteasome.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription by transcription factor localization

definition.value: Any process that stops, prevents, or reduces the frequency, rate or extent of DNA-dependent transcription using a mechanism that involves the localization of a transcription factor.

Any process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of gene expression. Gene expression is the process in which a gene's coding sequence is converted into a mature gene product or products (proteins or RNA). This includes the production of an RNA transcript as well as any processing to produce a mature RNA product or an mRNA (for protein-coding genes) and the translation of that mRNA into protein. Some protein processing events may be included when they are required to form an active form of a product from an inactive precursor form.

label.value: regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis

definition.value: A cell cycle process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis.

label.value: positive regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis

definition.value: A cell cycle process that increases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis.

label.value: negative regulation of transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis

definition.value: A cell cycle process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of transcription from an RNA polymerase II promoter during meiosis.

label.value: negative regulation of cellular carbohydrate metabolic process by negative regulation of transcription, DNA-templated

definition.value: Any cellular process that decreases the rate, extent or frequency of the chemical reactions and pathways involving carbohydrates carried out by repression of transcription.

label.value: negative regulation of ribosomal protein gene transcription from RNA polymerase II promoter

definition.value: Any process that decreases the frequency, rate or extent of the synthesis of RNA from ribosomal protein genes by RNA polymerase II, originating at an RNA polymerase II promoter.
